Interpreting the experimenter race x whiteAsian interaction: Across the board, participants chose more Asian than white people, but the effect was stronger when the experimenter was Asian (p < .001) compared to white (p = .004).

Does this two way interaction effect differ by stereotype dimension?

There is no three way interaction between whiteBlack:experimenterRace:dimension OR whiteAsian:experimenterRace:dimension. However, the pairwise contrast did reveal significant 3 way interaction effect. It could be that effect was detected with a small effect size/power, as well as effect from 2 way interaction. That said, there is no need to look at the pairwise contrast when the 3 way interaction is not significant in the model. However, this does open up possibility of running this study unmoderated where experimenter effect is removed (study 2).

  1. Do the choice differ by child age?

Yes, although age does not directly affect childrens choices (p = .43), there is a significant interaction between age and target race, specifically when comparing white and asian target (F = 3.24, p = 0.01). This means that the difference between Asian and White target choice scores changes with age. As children get older, they tend to choose Asian targets more than White targets, whereas there is no significant age effect for the Black versus White contrast. Through pairwise comparisons, such tendency to choose Asian targets over White targets is not found among 6-year-olds (p = 0.08), but seen among 7- to 10-year-olds (all p< 0.05).

There is also a significant three-way interaction whiteAsian:age:dimensionC (p = 0.04)

  1. Do the choice differ by childrens own race and gender background?

effect of childrens own race

Childrens choice on target race do not differ by their own race (omnibus test p = .68)

When using dichotomous variables to measure childrens race, the effect is still not significant (p = .26)

effect of childrens own gender

Childrens choice on target do no differ significantly based on childrens own gender (p = 0.31)

However, childrens choice on target gender differ significantly based on their own gender (p<0.001).

unpack the Gender * targetGender interaction

The target gender of childrens choice differ by their own gender. Girls tend to choose woman target more than boys (p<0.001); boys tend to choose man target more than girls (p<0.001).
